			<head id="a1">DESCRIPTIVE SUMMARY</head>
			<unittitle encodinganalog="MARC 245" label="Title:">Cuneiform tablets, </unittitle><unitdate certainty="approximate" encodinganalog="MARC 245" type="inclusive">2500 B.C.E.</unitdate>
			<unitid label="Collection Number:">6906</unitid>
			<origination label="Creator:"/>
			<physdesc encodinganalog="MARC 300" label="Quantity:"><extent>197 items</extent></physdesc><physdesc>Extent is approximate.</physdesc>
			<physdesc label="Forms of Material:">Clay tablets.</physdesc>
			<repository label="Repository:">Division of Rare and Manuscript Collections, Cornell
				University Library</repository>
			<abstract label="Abstract:">Cuneiform tablets (tablets made of clay, stone, metal, or
				wax, and inscribed with a wedge-shaped stylus) from the Old Babylonian period in
				ancient Mesopotamia, roughly the site of modern Iraq. Most are records of business
				transactions.</abstract>
			<langmaterial label="Language:">Collection material in <language encodinganalog="041" langcode="akk">Akkadian</language></langmaterial>
		</did>
		<scopecontent encodinganalog="MARC 520">
			<head id="a3">COLLECTION DESCRIPTION</head>
			<p>Cuneiform tablets (tablets made of clay, stone, metal, or wax, and inscribed with a
				wedge-shaped stylus) from the Old Babylonian period in ancient Mesopotamia, roughly
				the site of modern Iraq. Most are records of business transactions.</p>
		</scopecontent>
